		title: "#Seo-Yeon",
		text: "Zwischen Listening und Reading bekommen wir eine Viertel Stunde Pause und ich frage Seo-Yeon, ob sie sich mit mir einen Café holen will. Sie folgt mir, ohne von ihrem Handy aufzuschauen.<br>Dann stöhnt sie kurz auf und flucht auf Koreanisch. <br>„Yes, please?“ <br>„Ich weiß nicht. Einige Leute sind wirklich komisch.“ <br>„Ok.“ <br>„Jeder redet mit irgendwem auf einer Party und glaubt zu wissen, wer du bist. Als wäre man nachts um zwei dieselbe Person wie 12 stunden danach. Naja … aber eigentlich mag ich das. Dass man einfach … wie sagt man … verschwinden kann.“„Wie bitte?“ <br>„Ich mag, dass man einfach verschwinden kann.“ <br>„Ich verstehe kein Wort. Also ich meine inhaltlich, ich meine …“<br>„Ich schreibe gerade auf WeChat mit jemandem, den ich auf einer Party getroffen habe …“<br>„Seo-Yeon, can you do me a favour?“ <br>„Was denn?“ <br>„This is our break. I’m tired of Mandarin, please let’s speak English at least during our break.“ <br>„Gail, we speak Chinese when we are sober. But when us two meet, 85% of the time we’re drunk. What is your problem? Are you being a pussy about the other 15%?“<br>„I don’t care. This is my fucking break.“ <br>„Jeezuz, what is the matter with you, Chinese lady. You have some kinda Sinophobia?“ <br>„Yes, I do.“ <br>Sie lacht. <br>„Gail … Gail …“<br>„What?“ <br>„I don’t understand you. I would very much like to practice my Chinese – Ja, einen Latte Macchiato mit fettarmer Milch bitte. Haben Sie nicht? Dann normal.“ <br>„Seo-Yeon, your Chinese skills are intimidating.“ <br>„I know.“ <br>„Then what, you want to turn into a Chinese? A piece of Chineseness? A milestone of Chinese culture itself?“ <br>Wir verbrennen uns fast am Kaffe. Ich nehme den Deckel ab und schmeiße ihn weg.<br>„Let me make this clear to you: no, I do certainly not want to become a Chinese. And another thing: I know nothing about the Chinese culture. All I want to do is improve my Mandarin. That’s all.“ <br>Dann verzeiht sie ihr Gesicht und schmeißt den fast vollen Latte Macchiato in den Müll. „Grossest Latte Ever – I know you’re the unchinesiest Chinese alive but you are probably more Chinese than me. At least … you are used to the ways of your Chinese family. Maybe your dad has told you things about your country’s history, like most dads like to do, lecture you on something.“ <br>„Bullshit, how will you speak Chinese, wenn you have absolutely no clue about Chinese people and their ways? A contradiction in itself, gawd are we really having this conversation?“ <br>„Of course I know a little about Chinese ways, a few Chengyus, but most of all this doesn’t seem to be that different from Korea. It that sense, you may be right.“ <br>„So by Chinese way You mean …“, Ich atme durch, „You live to get rich und share your wealth with your parents. You don’t get a Phd because no averagely successful man would marry a Phd or because while you’re doing your Phd you would miss the chance to marry and squeeze one’s out. You try not to get fat and do your yoga and leave the city to visit your family in the countryside or suburbs for Chinese new year, buy them the omiyage package that are sold for that occasion in every mall. Always buy the newest iPhone.  Work your ass off to finally get a vacation for 6 days in which you visit 5 European cities in 3 days. But when you come back home don’t forget to claim Chinese food to still be the best food in the world – “ <br>„Which it isn’t. Korean food is absolutely the best.“ <br>„No … or maybe yes. I dunno. See? I’m not even convinced about the very thing every single Chinese soul should be completely convinced about.“ <br>„Is it really a Chinese thing?“ <br>„What? The life you described jut before.“ <br>„I think, yes.“ <br>„How do you know? You don’t barely talk to a Chinese.“ <br>„C’mon, I can’t talk to them. It disgusts me.“ <br>„There we are again.“ <br>Ich denke darüber nach, ob ich gerade die Wahrheit behaupte. Aber ich sehe sie an, als wüsste ich, was ich sage. <br>Ich wiederhole: „It disgusts me.“ <br>Seo-Yeon verdreht auf eine sehr delikate Art ihre Augen, sodass ich mir überlege mehr Dinge zu sagen, die sie aufregen. <br>„You know“, sage ich, „I have reconsidered. The thing I said about a Shanghainese life … the Chinese version would be that you want all these things but you would not necessarily be able to afford all of it.“ <br>Seo-Yeon sieht  mich an und schüttelt ungläubig mit ihrem Kopf. <br>„Gail, who cares? Why make all these differences between … lives or … I dunno places? And c’mon tell me, be honest. Is it such a different way of living in Germany?“ <br>„I think your problem is … in ur head. The only thing that is different is  the language. Und deswegen möchte ich noch mehr Chinesisch sprechen. Auch mit dir. Würde dir auch guttun.“ <br>„Oh, c’mon. You’re doing it for your CV, hoping it will get you one interview further isn’t it?“ <br>„Who here is not doing it for that exact reason?“ <br>„I don’t know maybe this Igor guy. Hardcore sinologist.“ <br>„Oh that one. He’s nuts isn’t he? Isn’t he the one who wants to fuck 100 Chinese virgins to … walk the confucian path?“ <br>„Yeah, daoist, I think.“ <br>„Uhm … probably none of that.“ <br>„Yeah whatever. It’s not like the people here are suffering from all the floods of international students willing to master Mandarin. Trust me, they make tons of money. It’s a freaking market.“ <br>„How do you know Igor by the way?“ <br>„Everybody knows Igor. He’s famous. Everyone’s scared to talk to him. Which is why everyone knows him. But he’s a very handsome lad, don’t you think?“ <br>„True … Do you also know this girl who is sitting on the stairway between the 5th and th 6th floor?“ <br>„You know the … Mongolian looking one?“ <br>„Yepp, I don’t know where she is from though. I have seen her at parties during the first two weeks or so, but now she is wearing no make up and is sitting on the stairs all by herself. First I didn’t recognise her without all the make up. She looks pretty young.“ <br>„Well, they are all toddlers in my eyes.“ <br>„I wonder what happened to her.“ <br>„Probably what happened to all of us. Too much drinking and shopping during the first two weeks that it made her broke.“ <br>„I mean it, Seo-Yeon.“ <br>„Sorry. She smokes often right?“ <br>„I think so. Never makes eye contact. <br>„Hm…yeah, I wonder what will be with her.“ <br><br>Wir kommen etwas zu spät aus der Pause zurück und lenken die gesamte Klasse ab, weil wir einmal durch alle Reihen laufen um in die letzte zurückzukehren. Der Lehrer ruft nacheinander die Leute auf, damit sie Teile aus dem Lehrbuchtext vorlesen.<br>„You know maybe“, flüstert Seo-Yeon, „the Mongolian girl ist just hanging out on the stairways during that time because her roomate’s got a visitor … and you know … they’re tangling in the sheets. So … don’t worry Mother Teresa.“ <br>Hier kommen mir Fremde manchmal vor wie Familie und Freunde werden einem fremd. Und in meinen eigenen Träumen komme ich selbst nicht mehr vor.",
